### 📌 How Spring Boot Uses This Internally

```java
// Spring Boot's main class IS a Java config class
@SpringBootApplication   // = @Configuration + @ComponentScan + @EnableAutoConfiguration
public class MyApp {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        SpringApplication.run(MyApp.class, args);
    }
}
```

```
@SpringBootApplication
    │
    ├── @Configuration          → this class can define beans
    ├── @ComponentScan          → scan all @Component in package
    └── @EnableAutoConfiguration→ loads Spring Boot's built-in @Configuration classes
                                   (DataSource, JPA, Security etc.)
```

> Every Spring Boot auto-config (like `DataSourceAutoConfiguration`) is just a `@Configuration` class with `@Bean` methods — exactly what you just learned.

---

### 📊 XML vs Java Config — Side by Side

| | XML Config | Java Config |
|---|---|---|
| File type | `beans.xml` | `AppConfig.java` |
| Bean definition | `<bean>` tag | `@Bean` method |
| Load context | `ClassPathXmlApplicationContext` | `AnnotationConfigApplicationContext` |
| Type safe | ❌ | ✅ |
| Refactor friendly | ❌ | ✅ |
| Used in Spring Boot | ❌ | ✅ |
| IDE support | Limited | Full |

---

### 🔑 Interview One-Liner
> "`@Configuration` marks a class as a Spring config file replacement for `beans.xml`. `@Bean` methods define beans manually — giving full Java type-safety. Spring Boot's `@SpringBootApplication` is itself a `@Configuration` class, and all auto-configuration is built on this same mechanism."
